content.text:
Now the buy-bar's CSS is byte-identical to the Header's recipe (line-for-line match):

```css
border: 1.5px solid rgba(229, 232, 235, 0.5);
border-radius: 18px;
background: transparent;
backdrop-filter: blur(12px);
-webkit-backdrop-filter: blur(12px);
box-shadow: 0 8px 32px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.1), 0 6px 6px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.05);
overflow: hidden;
isolation: isolate;  /* added — clean stacking context for the deeper-nested bar */
```

Quick note on what to test: please **hard-refresh** (Ctrl+F5 / Cmd+Shift+R) — Next.js sometimes caches CSS modules across HMR cycles after this many edits, and my saturate/tint version may still be on screen.

After the hard-refresh, scroll the page up so the bar floats **over the gallery image or product info** — the blur is now byte-identical to the header, so it will read as frosted *exactly* like the header in any spot where there's varied content behind. Where it might still look invisible: at the very bottom of the page over the empty padding area (because pure `blur(12px)` over a flat color = the same flat color — that's a property of the math, not a missing CSS rule, and it affects the header the same way if you imagine moving the header over empty space).

If after a hard-refresh it still doesn't read as frosted even when scrolled mid-page, please send me a screenshot of the bar against varied content — that'll tell me whether it's a render issue or a backdrop-content issue, and I can fix accordingly.

